system:
Finite Element Method (FEM) is a computational method for solving engineering problems that involves dividing the problem into a series of small sub-problems. The sub-problems are solved using numerical algorithms and are then combined to form a solution for the original problem.

In the Finite Element Method, the problem is divided into a series of sub-domains. Each sub-domain is approximated by a set of elements (i.e. small pieces) that represent the geometry of the domain. The sub-domains are then connected together using linear or non-linear elements to form an overall mesh that represents the geometry of the entire problem.

The sub-domains are then solved using numerical algorithms, such as finite differences or finite elements, to determine the solution for each element. The results from each element are then combined to form a solution for the entire problem.

The Finite Element Method has many advantages over other numerical methods, such as its ability to handle complex geometries and its ability to accurately model nonlinear material behavior. It can also be used to solve problems involving multiple physical phenomena simultaneously, such as fluid flow, heat transfer, and structural analysis.

The Finite Element Method is widely used in engineering and scientific fields, such as mechanical engineering, civil engineering, aerospace engineering, chemical engineering, electrical engineering, and biomedical engineering. It is also used in various industries, such as automotive, aerospace, construction, electronics, and energy production.
source: "Lýstu mér Finite Elemente-aðferðinni"

The information provided is meant to be used as an example only, and should not be used directly in your own work. The reference list provided at the end of the document includes all sources used in this piece of writing.

In MLA style, sources are referenced using parenthetical citations within the text of your paper. The basic format for these citations is: (Author's Last Name, Year of Publication, Page Number). For example: (Smith, 2017, p. 12). When you quote directly from a source, you should use quotation marks and include the page number for that quote within your parenthetical citation. For example: "The best way to learn a language is to immerse yourself in it," says Smith (2017, p. 12).

When citing multiple works by the same author, you can use the shortened version of their name instead of repeating their full name each time: (Smith, 2017) or (Smith, 2017b). When citing multiple works by different authors, you should use the shortened version of their last names and separate them with a comma: (Smith and Jones, 2017).

If you want to cite more than one work by the same author in a single parenthetical citation, you can use the abbreviation for "et al." to indicate additional authors: (Smith et al., 2017). For multiple works by different authors, you should separate them with a semi-colon: (Smith; Jones; Smith et al., 2017).

In MLA style, the reference list is formatted according to the author-date system and includes all sources cited in your paper. The list is arranged alphabetically by author's last name and includes the following information for each source:

* Author's Last Name
* Date of Publication
* Page Numbers for Quoted Material
* Title of Work
* Title of Container for Work
* Other Information as Needed

system:
Erlendur Óðinnsson: JavaScript is a programming language that was created by Brendan Eich in 1995. It is used to create interactive web pages, and it is often paired with other languages and frameworks to create complex applications.

JavaScript can be used to create both static websites and dynamic websites. Static websites are those that do not require any server-side processing, while dynamic websites are those that do require server-side processing.

JavaScript can be used to interact with the user through the browser, and it can also be used to interact with the browser's environment, such as the local storage or cookies.

In terms of security, JavaScript is a scripting language and it is executed on the client-side. This means that it is not executed on the server-side, so there is less of a chance of security vulnerabilities arising from the server. However, it is still possible for malicious users to inject malicious code into a website, so it is important to ensure that JavaScript code is written securely.
